04703nam a22006735i 9780292797413DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212004txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927974137 a10.7560/7028822doi  a(DE-B1597)587784  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aHIS0330002bisacsh1 aChristiansen, Tanja, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDisobedience, Slander, Seduction, and Assault :bWomen and Men in Cajamarca, Peru, 1862-1900 /cTanja Christiansen. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2004  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Presenting the Case -- t2. Cajamarcan Society under the Magnifying Glass: Regional Society, Economy, and Politics in the Nineteenth Century -- t3. Legislating Gender: The Law, Official Gender Norms, and Notions of Honor -- t4. Survival Strategies: Negotiating Matrimony -- t5. Injurias Verbales y Calumnias: Slander -- t6. Rapto, Seducción, Violación, and Estupro: Moving beyond the Loss of Honor -- t7. Conflict and Cooperation among Women -- t8. Conclusion -- tAppendix a Marital and Literacy Data from Criminal Trials, 1862–1900 -- tAppendix b Data from the National Census Conducted in 1876 -- tAppendix c Cited Trials -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough the law and courts of nineteenth-century Peru were institutions created by and for the ruling elite, women of all classes used the system to negotiate the complexities of property rights, childrearing, and marriage, and often to defend their very definitions of honor. Drawing on the trial transcripts of Cajamarca, a northern Peruvian province, from more than a century ago, this book shares eye-opening details about life among this community, in which reputation could determine a woman's chances of survival. Exploring the processes of courtship, seduction, and familial duties revealed in these court records, historian Tanja Christiansen has unearthed a compelling panorama that includes marital strife, slander, disobedience, street brawls, and spousal abuse alongside documents that give evidence of affection and devotion. Her research also yields much new information about the protocols for conflict and cooperation among nineteenth-century Peruvian women from all social strata, and the prevalence of informal unions in an economy driven in large part by migratory male labor. Reviving a little-known aspect of Latin American history, Christiansen's book simultaneously brings to light an important microcosm of women's history during the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHonorzPeruzCajamarca (Department)xHistoryy19th century. 0aMan-woman relationshipszPeruzCajamarca (Department)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSex rolezPeruzCajamarca (Department)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSexual ethicszPeruzCajamarca (Department)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial controlzPeruzCajamarca (Department)xHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenxSexual behaviorzPeruzCajamarca (Department)xHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenzPeruzCajamarca (Department)xSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aWorking classxSexual behaviorzPeruzCajamarca (Department)xHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70288240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292797413423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292797413/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11S